[31m-## 📖 Overview[m
[31m-[m
[31m-Picture a stadium holding **80,000+ fans** on World Cup final day. Gates are surging, concourses are packing shoulder-to-shoulder, and ops teams are relying on radio calls and gut instinct to figure out where the next bottleneck will break.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-**ZoneWatch AI** turns a single crowd photo into an actionable operations briefing in seconds. Upload an image from any zone — a gate, a concourse, an exit ramp — and Google Gemini's vision and reasoning capabilities do the rest: estimating density, spotting hazards, and generating clear, role-specific instructions for the people who need to act on them.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-It's not a dashboard that shows you numbers. It's a copilot that tells you **what's wrong and what to do about it.**[m
[31m-[m
[31m----[m
[31m-[m
[31m-## ❗ Problem Statement[m
[31m-[m
[31m-Large-scale tournaments like the FIFA World Cup 2026 concentrate massive crowds into fixed physical spaces, and the operational reality on the ground is tough:[m
[31m-[m
[31m-- 🚧 **Congestion builds faster than humans can monitor** — by the time a bottleneck is reported, it's already a safety risk.[m
[31m-- 👀 **Manual crowd monitoring doesn't scale** — CCTV feeds and radio reports depend entirely on how many eyes are watching, and where.[m
[31m-- 🌐 **Fans and staff speak different languages** — critical safety messaging often reaches only part of the crowd.[m
[31m-- 📋 **Decisions lag behind reality** — stewards and organizers frequently react to congestion instead of preventing it.[m
[31m-- ♿ **Accessibility and safety needs are easy to miss** — blocked aisles or lost egress routes can go unnoticed until it's too late.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-The result: slower response times, avoidable safety incidents, and a degraded experience for fans — exactly when stakes and crowd volumes are at their highest.[m
[31m-[m
[31m----[m
[31m-[m
[31m-## 💡 Solution[m
[31m-[m
[31m-**ZoneWatch AI** closes the gap between *seeing* a problem and *acting* on it.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-1. A photo from any stadium zone is uploaded (or pulled from a camera feed in future versions).[m
[31m-2. **Google Gemini's Vision API** analyzes the image directly — reading crowd density, spacing, and visible hazards.[m
[31m-3. Gemini's **generative reasoning** converts that visual read into a structured operational brief: risk level, hazard description, and a recommended action.[m
[31m-4. The system auto-drafts **two outputs** — an internal instruction for staff, and a calm, fan-facing safety message.[m
[31m-5. Everything lands on a live, zone-based **operations dashboard** so teams can monitor multiple areas at once.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-The result is a tool that doesn't just flag a problem — it tells the right person, in the right words, exactly what to do next.[m
[31m-[m
